      <H1>Terrain Generation Tutorial: Code<BR></H1><SPAN =
class=3Dsubnav><A=20
      =
href=3D"http://www.robot-frog.com/3d/hills/island.html">previous</A> | =
next=20
      | code</SPAN>=20
      <P>I've written a complete C++ class you can use to generate =
terrains=20
      using the described algorithm. The class takes care of managing =
the=20
      heightmap memory for you as well. It does not perform any =
rendering; it=20
      only creates and generates the heightmaps. It has parameters to =
allow you=20
      to set the size of the heightmap, the range of hill sizes, the =
number of=20
      hills, whether or not to generate and island, the amount of =
flattening,=20
      and the random seed used. To use it, all you need to do is =
this:</P><PRE>#include "rfHillTerrain.h"

using namespace RobotFrog; // the class is in this namespace

int main( void )
{
    HillTerrain terrain(); // you can also specify terrain params here
    terrain.Generate();
       =20
    for( int x =3D 0; x &lt; terrain.GetSize(); ++x )
    {
        for( int y =3D 0; y &lt; terrain.GetSize(); ++y )
        {
            float z =3D terrain.GetCell( x, y );
            // do whatever with the z values here to draw your terrain
        }
    }
}</PRE>
      <P>The constructor has parameters for all of the variables =
affecting the=20
      algorithm. In addition, you can also change the parameters on an =
existing=20
      terrain and regenerate it. The terrain also stores the random seed =
it uses=20
      to generate itself so that you can create the same terrain when =
you need=20
      to.</P>
      <H2>Platforms</H2>
      <P>The code has been tested and it runs fine on MacOS and Windows. =
It=20
      should theoretically run without problems on any platform that has =

      &lt;math.h&gt; for sin() and cos(), &lt;stdlib.h&gt; for rand() =
and=20
      srand(), &lt;assert.h&gt; for assert(), and &lt;new.h&gt; for=20
      std::bad_alloc. The class is put inside the namespace RobotFrog, =
so you=20
      will need to either specify the namespace when using it, or just =
import=20
      it. The constructor also throws an exception if it can't allocate =
enough=20
      memory, so you will need to enable exception handling.</P>
      <H2>Inheritance</H2>
      <P>The class was not designed to be inherited, but if you felt =
like=20
      implementing other algorithms using it as a base, it should be =
fairly easy=20
      to modify. Basically, you would need to make Generate() virtual, =
and then=20
      override it. </P>
